#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:1742
#, no-c-format
msgid "Configuring policies for failover, queuing, and failback"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1744
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The goal of multipath I/O is to provide connectivity fault tolerance between "
"the storage system and the server. The desired default behavior depends on "
"whether the server is a stand-alone server or a node in a high-availability "
"cluster."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1750
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This section discusses the most important <systemitem>multipath-tools</"
"systemitem> configuration parameters for achieving fault tolerance."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1757
#, no-c-format
msgid "polling_interval"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1759
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The time interval (in seconds) between health checks for path\t devices. "
"The default is 5 seconds. Failed devices are checked at\t this time "
"interval. For healthy devices, the time interval may be\t increased up to "
"<literal>max_polling_interval</literal> seconds.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1768
#, no-c-format
msgid "detect_checker"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1770
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If this is set to <literal>yes</literal> (default, recommended),\t "
"<command>multipathd</command> automatically detects the best path\t checking "
"algorithm.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1778
#, no-c-format
msgid "path_checker"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1780
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The algorithm used to check path state. If you need to set this,\t do not "
"forget to set also\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:1784
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"defaults {\n"
"\t  detect_checker no\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1788
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The following list contains only the most important algorithms. See\t "
"<systemitem>multipath.conf(5)</systemitem> for the full list.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1794
#, no-c-format
msgid "tur"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1796
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tSend TEST UNIT READY command. This is the default for SCSI\t\tdevices "
"with ALUA support.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1803
#, no-c-format
msgid "directio"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1805
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t\tRead a device sector using asynchronous I/O (aio).\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1811
#, no-c-format
msgid "rdac"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1813
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t\tDevice-specific checker for NetAPP E-Series and similar arrays.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1819
#, no-c-format
msgid "none"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1821
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t\tNo path checking is performed.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1830
#, no-c-format
msgid "\tchecker_timeout"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1834
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If a device doesn't respond to a path checker command in the given\t "
"time, it is considered failed. The default is the kernel's SCSI\t command "
"timeout for the device (usually 30 seconds).\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1842
#, no-c-format
msgid "\tfast_io_fail_tmo"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1846
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If an error on the SCSI transport layer is detected (for example on\t a "
"Fibre Channel remote port), the kernel transport layer waits for this\t "
"amount of time (in seconds) for the transport to recover. After that, the "
"path\t device fails with \"transport offline\" state. This is very useful for"
"\t multipath, because it allows quick path failover for a frequently occuring"
"\t class of errors. The value must match typical time scale for\t "
"reconfiguration in the fabric. The default value of 5 seconds works\t well "
"for Fibre Channel. Other transports, like iSCSI,\t may require longer "
"timeouts.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1860
#, no-c-format
msgid "\tdev_loss_tmo"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1864
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If a SCSI transport endpoint (for example a Fibre Channel remote\t port) "
"is not reachable any more, the kernel waits for this amount of time\t (in "
"seconds)\t for the port to reappear until it removes the SCSI device node "
"for good.\t Device node removal is a complex operation which is prone to race"
"\t conditions or deadlocks, and should best be avoided. It is therefore\t "
"recommended to set this to a high value. The special value\t "
"<literal>infinity</literal> is supported. The default is 10 minutes.\t In "
"order to avoid deadlock situations,\t <command>multipathd</command> ensures "
"that I/O queueing (see\t <literal>no_path_retry</literal> ) is stopped\t "
"before <literal>dev_loss_tmo</literal> expires.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1881
#, no-c-format
msgid "no_path_retry"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1883
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Determine what happens if all paths of a given multipath map have\t "
"failed. The possible values are:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1889
#, no-c-format
msgid "fail"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1891
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Fail I/O on the multipath map. This will cause I/O errors in\t upper "
"layers such as mounted file systems. The affected\t file systems, and "
"possibly the entire host, will enter\t degraded mode.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1900
#, no-c-format
msgid "queue"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1902
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t I/O on the multipath map is queued in the device-mapper\t layer and sent "
"to the device when path devices become available\t again. This is the safest "
"option to avoid losing data, but it\t can have negative effects if the path "
"devices don't get\t reinstated for a long time. Processes reading from the "
"device\t will hang in uninterruptible sleep\t ( <literal>D</literal> ) state."
"\t Queued data occupies memory, which becomes unavailable\t for processes. "
"Eventually, memory will be exhausted.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1918
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t <replaceable>N</replaceable> is a positive integer.\t Keep the map device "
"in queuing mode for <replaceable>N</replaceable> \t polling intervals. When "
"the time elapses, <command>multipathd</command> fails the map\t device. If "
"<literal>polling_interval</literal> is 5 seconds and\t "
"<literal>no_path_retry</literal> is 6,\t <command>multipathd</command> will "
"queue I/O for approximately\t 6 * 5s = 30s before failing I/O on the map "
"device.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1933
#, no-c-format
msgid "flush_on_last_del"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1935
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If set to <literal>yes</literal> and all path devices of a map are\t "
"deleted (as opposed to just failed), fail all I/O in the map\t before "
"removing it. The default is <literal>no</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1943
#, no-c-format
msgid "deferrred_remove"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1945
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If set to <literal>yes</literal> and all path devices of a map are\t "
"deleted, wait for holders to close the file descriptors for the map\t device "
"before flushing and removing it.\t If paths reappear before the the last "
"holder closed the map,\t the deferred remove operation will be cancelled.\t "
"The default is <literal>no</literal> .\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1956
#, no-c-format
msgid "failback"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1958
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If a failed path device in an inactive path group\t recovers, "
"<command>multipathd</command> reevaluates the path\t group priorities of all "
"path groups\t (see <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-grouping\" xrefstyle="
"\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ).\t After the reevaluation, the\t highest-priority "
"path group\t may be one of the currently inactive path groups. This parameter"
"\t determines what happens in this situation."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:1969
#, no-c-format
msgid "Observe vendor recommendations"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1970
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The optimal failback policy depends on the property of the storage\t "
"device. It's therefore strongly encouraged to verify\t <option>failback</"
"option> settings with the storage vendor.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1978
#, no-c-format
msgid "manual"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1980
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Nothing happens unless the administrator runs a\t <command>multipathd "
"switchgroup</command> \t (see <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-mpiotools-"
"multipathd\" xrefstyle=\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ).\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:1989
#, no-c-format
msgid "immediate"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:1991
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The highest-priority path group is activated immediately.\t This is often "
"beneficial for performance, especially on\t standalone servers, but it "
"shouldn't be used for arrays on which\t path group changing is a costly "
"operation.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2000
#, no-c-format
msgid "followover"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2002
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Like <literal>immediate</literal> , but only perform failback\t when the "
"path that has just become active is the only healthy\t path in its path "
"group. This is useful for cluster\t configurations: It keeps a node from "
"automatically failing back\t when another node requested a failover before.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2012
#, no-c-format
msgid "<replaceable>N</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2014
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t <replaceable>N</replaceable> is a positive integer.\t Wait for "
"<replaceable>N</replaceable> polling intervals before\t activating the "
"highest priority path group. If the priorities\t change again during this "
"time, the wait period starts anew.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2026
#, no-c-format
msgid "eh_deadline"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2028
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Set an approximate upper limit for\t the time (in seconds) spent in SCSI "
"error handling if devices are\t unresponsive and SCSI commands time out "
"without error response.\t When the deadline has elapsed, the kernel will "
"perform a full HBA reset.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2043
#, no-c-format
msgid "Queueing policy on standalone servers"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2046
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"When you configure multipath I/O for a stand-alone server, a "
"<literal>no_path_retry</literal> setting with value <literal>queue</literal> "
"protects the server operating system from receiving I/O errors as long as "
"possible. It queues messages until a multipath failover occurs. If &ldquo;"
"infinite&rdquo; queueing is not desired (see above), select a numeric value "
"that's deemed high enough for the storage paths to recover under ordinary "
"circumstances (see above)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2058
#, no-c-format
msgid "Queueing policy on clustered servers"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2061
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"When you configure multipath I/O for a node in a high-availability cluster, "
"you want multipath to report the I/O failure to trigger the resource "
"failover instead of waiting for a multipath failover to be resolved. In "
"cluster environments, you must modify the <literal>no_path_retry </literal> "
"setting so that the cluster node receives an I/O error in relation to the "
"cluster verification process (recommended to be 50% of the heartbeat "
"tolerance) if the connection is lost to the storage system. In addition, you "
"want the multipath <literal>failback</literal> to be set to <literal>manual</"
"literal> or <literal>followover</literal> to avoid a ping-pong of resources "
"because of path failures."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2077
#, no-c-format
msgid "Configuring path grouping and priorities"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2079
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Path devices in multipath maps are grouped in <emphasis>path groups</"
"emphasis> , also called <emphasis>priority groups</emphasis> . Only one path "
"group receives I/O at any given time. <command>multipathd</command> assigns "
"<emphasis>priorities</emphasis> to path groups. Out of the path groups with "
"active paths, the group with the highest priority is activated according to "
"the configured failback policy for the map (see <xref linkend=\"sec-"
"multipath-policies-default\" xrefstyle=\"SecTitleOnPage\"/> ). The priority "
"of a path group is the average of the priorities of the active path devices "
"in the path group. The priority of a path device is an integer value "
"calculated from the device properties (see the description of the "
"<literal>prio</literal> option below)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2093
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This section describes the <filename>multipath.conf</filename> configuration "
"parameters relevant for priority determination and path grouping."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2099
#, no-c-format
msgid "path_grouping_policy"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2101
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Specifies the method used combine paths\t into groups. Only the most "
"important policies are listed here;\t see <systemitem>multipath.conf(5)</"
"systemitem> for other\t less frequently used values.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2109
#, no-c-format
msgid "failover"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2111
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tOne path per path group. This setting is useful\t\tfor traditional "
"&ldquo;active/passive&rdquo; storage arrays.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2118
#, no-c-format
msgid "multibus"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2120
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tAll paths in one path group.\t\tThis is useful for traditional &ldquo;"
"active/active&rdquo;\t\tarrays.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2128
#, no-c-format
msgid "group_by_prio"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2130
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tPath devices with the same path priority are grouped\t\ttogether.\t"
"\tThis option is useful for modern arrays that support\t\tasymmetric access "
"states, like ALUA.\t\tCombined with the <literal>alua</literal> or\t\t "
"<literal>sysfs</literal> priority algorithms, the priority\t\tgroups set up "
"by <command>multipathd</command> will match the\t\tprimary target port "
"groups that the storage array reports through\t\tALUA-related SCSI commands."
"\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2144
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Using the same policy names, the path grouping policy for\t a multipath "
"map can be changed temporarily with the command\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2148
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;multipath -p <replaceable>POLICY_NAME</replaceable> "
"<replaceable>MAP_NAME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2154
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If set to <literal>on</literal> or <literal>fpin</literal> ,\t &ldquo;"
"marginal&rdquo; path devices are sorted into a separate path\t group. This "
"is independent of the path grouping algorithm in use.\t See <xref linkend="
"\"sec-multipath-marginal\" xrefstyle=\"SecTitleOnPage\"/> .\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2163
#, no-c-format
msgid "detect_prio"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2165
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If this is set to <literal>yes</literal> (default, recommended),\t "
"<command>multipathd</command> automatically detects the best\t algorithm to "
"set the priority for a storage device, and ignores\t the <literal>prio</"
"literal> setting.\t In practice, this means using the <literal>sysfs</"
"literal> prio\t algorithm if ALUA support is detected.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2176
#, no-c-format
msgid "prio"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2178
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Determines the method to derive priorities for path devices.\t If you "
"override this, don't forget to set also\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2182
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"defaults {\n"
"\t  detect_prio no\n"
"}\n"
"\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2187
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The following list\t contains only the most important methods. Several "
"other methods\t are available, mainly to support legacy hardware. See\t "
"<systemitem>multipath.conf(5)</systemitem> for the full list.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2195
#, no-c-format
msgid "alua"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2197
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tUses SCSI-3 ALUA access states to derive path priority values.\t\tThe "
"optional <literal>exclusive_pref_bit</literal> argument can be used to\t"
"\tchange the behavior for devices that have the ALUA\t\t&ldquo;preferred "
"primary target port group&rdquo;\t\t(PREF) bit set:\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2204
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"\tprio alua\n"
"\tprio_args exclusive_pref_bit\n"
"\t      "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2208
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tIf this option is set, &ldquo;preferred&rdquo; paths get a\t\tpriority "
"bonus over other active/optimized paths. Otherwise,\t\tall active/optimized "
"paths are assigned the same priority.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2216
#, no-c-format
msgid "sysfs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2218
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tLike <literal>alua</literal> , but instead of sending SCSI\t\tcommands "
"to the device, obtains the access states from\t\t <systemitem>sysfs</"
"systemitem> . This causes less I/O load\t\tthan <literal>alua</literal> , "
"but isn't suitable for all\t\tstorage arrays with ALUA support.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2228
#, no-c-format
msgid "const"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2230
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t\tUses a constant value for all paths.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2236
#, no-c-format
msgid "path_latency"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2238
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tMeasures I/O latency (time from I/O submission to completion)\t\ton path "
"devices, and assigns higher priority to devices with\t\tlower latency. See "
"<systemitem>multipath.conf(5)</systemitem> \t\tfor details. This algorithm "
"is still experimental.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2247
#, no-c-format
msgid "weightedpath"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2249
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tAssigns a priority to paths based on their name, serial\t\tnumber, Host:"
"Bus:Target:Lun ID (HBTL),\t\tor Fibre Channel WWN.\t\tThe priority value "
"doesn't change over time. The\t\tmethod requires a <literal>prio_args</"
"literal> argument, see\t\t <systemitem>multipath.conf(5)</systemitem> for "
"details. For example:\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2257
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"\tprio weightedpath\n"
"\tprio_args \"hbtl 2:.*:.*:.* 10 hbtl 3:.*:.*:.* 20 hbtl .* 1\"\n"
"\t      "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2261
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tThis assigns devices on SCSI host 3 a higher priority than\t\tdevices on "
"SCSI host 2, and all others a lower priority.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2271
#, no-c-format
msgid "prio_args"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2273
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Some <literal>prio</literal> algorithms require extra\t arguments. These "
"are specified in this option, with syntax depending\t on the algorithm. See "
"above.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2281
#, no-c-format
msgid "hardware_handler"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2283
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The name of a kernel module that the kernel uses to activate path\t "
"devices when switching path groups.\t This option has no effect with recent "
"kernels, because\t hardware handlers are autodetected. See <xref linkend="
"\"sec-multipath-hardware-handlers\" xrefstyle=\"SecTitleOnPage\"/> .\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2293
#, no-c-format
msgid "path_selector"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2295
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The name of a kernel module that is used for load balancing between\t the "
"paths of the active path group. The available choices depend on\t the kernel "
"configuration. For historical reasons, the name must always\t be enclosed in "
"quotes and followed by a &ldquo;0&rdquo; in\t <filename>multipath.conf</"
"filename> , like this:\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2302
#, no-c-format
msgid "path_selector \"queue-length 0\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2305
#, no-c-format
msgid "service-time"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2307
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tEstimates the time pending I/O will need to complete on all\t\tpaths, "
"and selects the path with the lowest value. This is the\t\tdefault.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2315
#, no-c-format
msgid "historical-service-time"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2317
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tEstimates future service time based on the historical\t\tservice time "
"(about which it keeps a moving average)\t\tand the number of outstanding "
"requests.\t\tEstimates the time pending I/O will need to complete on all\t"
"\tpaths, and selects the path with the lowest value.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2327
#, no-c-format
msgid "queue-length"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2329
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tSelects the path with the lowest number of currently pending\t\tI/O "
"requests.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2336
#, no-c-format
msgid "round-robin"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2338
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tSwitches paths in round-robin fashion. The number of requests\t"
"\tsubmitted to a path before switching to the next one can be\t\tadjusted "
"with the options <literal>rr_min_io_rq</literal> \t\tand <literal>rr_weight</"
"literal> .\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2347
#, no-c-format
msgid "io-affinity"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2349
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\tThis path selector does currently not work with <systemitem>multipath-"
"tools</systemitem> .\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2358
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"After modifying the <filename>/etc/multipath.conf</filename> file, apply "
"your settings as described in <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-conf-file-apply"
"\" xrefstyle=\"SecTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2365
#, no-c-format
msgid "Selecting devices for multipathing"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2367
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"On systems with multipath devices, it is sometimes desirable to avoid "
"setting up multipath maps on some devices (typically local disks). "
"<systemitem>multipath-tools</systemitem> offers various means for "
"configuring which devices should be considered multipath path devices, which "
"are described in this section."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2375
#, no-c-format
msgid "multipath on local disks"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2376
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In general, there is nothing wrong with setting up &ldquo;degraded&rdquo; "
"multipath maps with just a single device on top of local disks. It works "
"fine and requires no extra configuration. However, some administrators find "
"this confusing or generally oppose this sort of unnecessary multipathing. "
"Also, the multipath layer causes a slight performance overhead. See also "
"<xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-planning-type-noroot\" xrefstyle="
"\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2392
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>blacklist</literal> section in <filename>multipath.conf</"
"filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2393
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <filename>/etc/multipath.conf</filename> file can contain a "
"<literal>blacklist</literal> section where all devices are listed that "
"<command>multipathd</command> and <command>multipath</command> should "
"ignore. The following example illustrates possible ways for device "
"blacklisting:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2401
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"blacklist {\n"
"    wwid 3600605b009e7ed501f0e45370aaeb77f <co xml:id=\"mp-co-bl-wwid\"/>\n"
"    device {  <co xml:id=\"mp-co-bl-device\"/>\n"
"        vendor ATA\n"
"        product .*\n"
"    }\n"
"    protocol scsi:sas <co xml:id=\"mp-co-bl-prot\"/>\n"
"    property SCSI_IDENT_LUN_T10 <co xml:id=\"mp-co-bl-prop\"/>\n"
"    devnode \"!^dasd[a-z]*\" <co xml:id=\"mp-co-bl-devnode\"/>\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2413
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t <literal>wwid</literal> entries are ideal for excluding specific\t "
"devices, for example the root disk.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2419
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t This <literal>device</literal> section excludes all ATA devices\t (the "
"regular expression for <literal>product</literal> matches anything).\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2425
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Blacklisting by <literal>protocol</literal> allows excluding devices "
"using certain\t bus types, here SAS. Other common protocol values are\t "
"<literal>scsi:fcp</literal> ,\t <literal>scsi:iscsi</literal> , and "
"<literal>ccw</literal> . See\t <systemitem>multipath.conf(5)</systemitem> "
"for more. To see the\t protocols that paths in your systems are using, run\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2433
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;multipathd show paths format \"%d %P\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2434
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t This\t form is supported since\t &productnameshort;&nbsp;15 SP1 and "
"&productnameshort;&nbsp;12 SP5.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2441
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t This <literal>property</literal> entry excludes devices that have a\t "
"certain udev property (no matter what the value of the property is).\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2447
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Excluding devices by <literal>devnode</literal> is only recommended\t for "
"classes of devices, using regular expressions, like in the\t example, which "
"excludes everything but DASD devices.\t Using this for individual\t devices "
"like <filename>sda</filename> is discouraged, because\t device node names "
"are not persistent.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2455
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The example illustrates special syntax that is only supported in\t the "
"<literal>blacklist</literal> and\t <literal>blacklist_exceptions</literal> "
"sections: Prefixing the\t regular expression with an exclamation mark\t "
"( <literal>!</literal> ) negates the match. Note that the exclamation\t mark "
"must appear within double quotes.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2466
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"By default, <systemitem>multipath-tools</systemitem> ignores all devices "
"except SCSI, DASD, or NVMe. Technically, the built-in devnode blacklist is "
"this negated regular expression:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2471
#, no-c-format
msgid "devnode !^(sd[a-z]|dasd[a-z]|nvme[0-9])"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2474
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>blacklist exceptions</literal> section in <filename>multipath."
"conf</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2475
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Sometimes it is desired to configure only very specific devices for "
"multipathing. In this case, devices are excluded by default, and exceptions "
"are defined for devices that should be part of a multipath map. The "
"<literal>blacklist_exceptions</literal> section exists for this purpose. It "
"is typically used like in the following example, which excludes everything "
"except storage with product string &ldquo;NETAPP&rdquo;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2483
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"blacklist {\n"
"     wwid .*\n"
"}\n"
"blacklist_exceptions {\n"
"     device {\n"
"         vendor ^NETAPP$\n"
"         product .*\n"
"     }\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2492
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>blacklist_exceptions</literal> section supports all methods "
"described for the <literal>blacklist</literal> section above."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2496
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>property</literal> directive in <literal>blacklist_exceptions</"
"literal> is special, because every device <emphasis>must</emphasis> have at "
"least one of the &ldquo;whitelisted&rdquo; udev properties in order to be "
"condsidered as path device for multipath (the value of the property does not "
"matter). The built-in default for <literal>property</literal> is"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2504
#, no-c-format
msgid "property (SCSI_IDENT_|ID_WWN)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2505
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Only devices that have at least one udev property matching this regular "
"expression will be included."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2512
#, no-c-format
msgid "Other options affecting device selection"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2513
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Besides the blacklisting options, a few other settings in <filename>/etc/"
"multipath.conf</filename> affect which devices are considered multipath path "
"devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2520
#, no-c-format
msgid "find_multipaths"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2522
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t This option controls the behavior of <command>multipath</command> \t and "
"<command>multipathd</command> when a non-blacklisted device\t is first "
"encountered. The possible values are:\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2529
#, no-c-format
msgid "greedy"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2531
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\t Every non-blacklisted device is included.\t\t This is the default on "
"&opensuse; and &sle;\t\t distributions. If this setting is active, the only "
"way to\t\t prevent devices from being added to multipath maps is\t\t "
"blacklisting.\t\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2541
#, no-c-format
msgid "strict"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2543
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\t Every device is excluded, even if not blacklisted, unless\t\t its WWID "
"is listed in the file\t\t <filename>/etc/multipath/wwids</filename> .\t\t "
"This is the default in some other Linux distributions.\t\t It requires "
"manual maintenance of the WWIDs file (see\t\t note below).\t\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2554
#, no-c-format
msgid "yes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2556
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\t Devices are included if they meet the conditions for\t\t "
"<literal>strict</literal> , or if at least one other device\t\t with the "
"same WWID exists in the system.\t\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2564
#, no-c-format
msgid "smart"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2566
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\t If a new WWID is\t\t first encountered, it is temporarily marked as "
"multipath path\t\t device.\t\t <command>multipathd</command> waits for some "
"time for additional paths with\t\t the same WWID to appear. If this happens, "
"the multipath map\t\t is set up as usual. Otherwise, when\t\t the timeout "
"expires, the single device is released to\t\t the system as non-multipath "
"device.\t\t The timeout is configurable with the option\t\t "
"<option>find_multipaths_timeout</option> .\t\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2578
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\t This option depends on <command>systemd</command> features\t\t which "
"are only available on &sles;&nbsp;15.\t\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2586
#, no-c-format
msgid "Maintaining <filename>/etc/multipath/wwids</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2587
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t <systemitem>multipath-tools</systemitem> keeps a record of previously\t "
"set up multipath maps in the file\t <filename>/etc/multipath/wwids</"
"filename> (the &ldquo;WWIDs file&rdquo;).\t Devices with WWIDs listed in "
"this file are considered multipath\t path devices. The file is\t important "
"for multipath device selection for all values of\t <option>find_multipaths</"
"option> except <literal>greedy</literal> \t (users of <literal>greedy</"
"literal> can ignore this note)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2597
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If <option>find_multipaths</option> is set to <literal>yes</literal> or\t "
"<literal>smart</literal> , <command>multipathd</command> adds WWIDs to\t "
"<filename>/etc/multipath/wwids</filename> after setting up new maps,\t so "
"that these maps will be detected more quickly in the future."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2603
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t The WWIDs file can be manually modified::"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2607
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"&prompt.sudo;multipath -a 3600a098000aad1e3000064e45f2c2355 <co xml:id=\"mp-"
"co-wwid-a\"/>\n"
"&prompt.sudo;multipath -w /dev/sdf <co xml:id=\"mp-co-wwid-w\"/>\n"
"       "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2613
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t This command adds the given WWID to <filename>/etc/multipath/wwids</"
"filename> .\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2618
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t This command removes the WWID of the given device.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2624
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t In <literal>strict</literal> mode, this is the only way to add new\t "
"multipath devices.\t After modifying the WWIDs file, run <command>multipathd"
"\t reconfigure</command> to apply the changes. It is recommended to\t "
"rebuild the initramfs after applying changes to the WWIDs file\t (see <xref "
"linkend=\"sec-multipath-initrd-sync\" xrefstyle=\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2636
#, no-c-format
msgid "allow_usb_devices"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2638
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If this option is set to <literal>yes</literal> , USB storage\t devices "
"are considered for multipathing. The default is <literal>no</literal> .\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2648
#, no-c-format
msgid "Multipath device names and WWIDs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2650
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<command>multipathd</command> and <command>multipath</command> internally "
"use WWIDs to identify devices. WWIDs are also used as map names by default. "
"For convenience, <systemitem>multipath-tools</systemitem> supports assigning "
"simpler, easier memorizable names to multipath devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2659
#, no-c-format
msgid "WWIDs and device Identification"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2660
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It's crucial for multipath operation to reliably detect devices that "
"represent paths to the same storage volume. <systemitem>multipath-tools</"
"systemitem> use the device's World Wide Identification (WWID) for this "
"purpose (sometimes also referred to as Universally Unique ID (UUID) or "
"Unique ID (UID — don't confuse with &ldquo;User ID&rdquo;). The WWID of a "
"map device is always the same as the WWID of its path devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2669
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"By default, WWIDs of path devices are inferred from udev properties of the "
"devices, which are determined in udev rules, either by reading device "
"attributes from the sysfs file system or by using specifc I/O commands. To "
"see the udev properties of a device, run"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2675
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;udevadm info /dev/<replaceable>sdx</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2676
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The udev properties used by <systemitem>multipath-tools</systemitem> to "
"derive WWIDs are:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2682
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t <literal>ID_SERIAL</literal> for SCSI devices (don't confuse this\t with "
"the device's &ldquo;serial number&rdquo;),"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2688
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t <literal>ID_UID</literal> for DASD devices,"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2693
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t <literal>ID_WWN</literal> for NVMe devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2699
#, no-c-format
msgid "Avoid changing WWIDs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2700
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It is impossible to change the WWID of a multipath map which is in use. If "
"the WWID of mapped path devices changes because of a configuration change, "
"the map needs to be destroyed and a new map needs to be set up with the new "
"WWID. This can't be done while the old map is in use. In extreme cases, data "
"corruption may result from WWID changes. It must therefore be "
"<emphasis>strictly avoided</emphasis> to apply configuration changes that "
"would cause map WWIDs to change."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2710
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It is allowed to enable the <literal>uid_attrs</literal> option in "
"<filename>/etc/multipath.conf</filename> , See <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-"
"conf-misc\" xrefstyle=\"SecTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2718
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting aliases for multipath maps"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2719
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Arbitrary map names can be set in the <literal>multipaths</literal> section "
"of <filename>/etc/multipath.conf</filename> like this:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2723
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"multipaths {\n"
"    multipath {\n"
"        wwid 3600a098000aad1e3000064e45f2c2355\n"
"        alias postgres\n"
"    }\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2729
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Aliases are expressive, but they need to be assigned to each map "
"individually, which may be cumbersome on large systems."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2736
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using autogenerated user-friendly names"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2737
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<systemitem>multipath-tools</systemitem> also supports autogenerated "
"aliases, so-called &ldquo;user-friendly names&rdquo;. The naming scheme is "
"follows: A name prefix (by default, <literal>mpath</literal> ) is followed "
"by lower-case letters. <literal>mpatha</literal> is the first possible name, "
"followed by <literal>mpathb</literal> , <literal>mpathc</literal> , …, "
"<literal>mpathz</literal> . After that follows <literal>mpathaa</literal> , "
"<literal>mpathab</literal> , and so on."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2747
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Map names are only useful if they are persistent. <systemitem>multipath-"
"tools</systemitem> keeps track of the assigned names in the file <filename>/"
"etc/multipath/bindings</filename> (the &ldquo; bindings file&rdquo;). When a "
"new map is set up, the WWID is first looked up in this file. If it is not "
"found, the lowest available user-friendly name is assigned to it."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2756
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Explicit aliases as discussed in <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-alias\"/> "
"take precedence over user-friendly names."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2760
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following options in <filename>/etc/multipath.conf</filename> affect "
"user friendly names:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2766
#, no-c-format
msgid "user_friendly_names"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2768
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If set to <literal>yes</literal> , user friendly names are\t assigned and "
"used. Otherwise, the WWID is used as map name unless\t an alias is "
"configured.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2776
#, no-c-format
msgid "alias_prefix"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2778
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The prefix used to create user friendly names,\t <literal>mpath</literal> "
"by default.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2786
#, no-c-format
msgid "Map names in high-availability clusters"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2787
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For cluster operations, device names must be identical across all nodes in "
"the cluster. The <systemitem>multipath-tools</systemitem> configuration must "
"be kept synchronized between nodes. If <literal>user_friendly_names</"
"literal> is used, special care must be taken for <filename>/etc/multipath/"
"bindings</filename> , because it may be modified by <command>multipathd</"
"command> at run time. Such modifications must be replicated dynamically to "
"all nodes. The same applies to <filename>/etc/multipath/wwids</filename> "
"(see <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-device-select-other\" xrefstyle="
"\"SecTitleOnPage\"/> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2801
#, no-c-format
msgid "Changing map names at run time"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2802
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It is possible to change map names at run time. Use any of the methods "
"described in this section and run <command>multipathd reconfigure</"
"command> , and the maps names will change without disruption of system "
"operation."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2812
#, no-c-format
msgid "Referring to multipath maps"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2813
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Technically, multipath maps are Device Mapper devices, which have generic "
"names of the form <filename>/dev/dm-<replaceable>n</replaceable></filename> "
"with an integer number <replaceable>n</replaceable> . These names are not "
"persistent. They should <emphasis>never</emphasis> be used to refer to the "
"multipath maps. <command>udev</command> creates various symbolic links to "
"these devices, which are more suitable as persistent references. These links "
"differ with respect to their invariance against certain configuration "
"changes. The following typical example shows various symlinks all pointing "
"to the same device."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2826
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"/dev/disk/by-id/dm-name-mpathb<co xml:id=\"mp-ref-dm-name\"/> -&gt; ../../"
"dm-1\n"
"/dev/disk/by-id/dm-uuid-mpath-3600a098000aad73f00000a3f5a275dc8<co xml:id="
"\"mp-ref-dm-uuid\"/> -&gt; ../../dm-1\n"
"/dev/disk/by-id/scsi-3600a098000aad73f00000a3f5a275dc8<co xml:id=\"mp-ref-"
"scsi\"/> -&gt; ../../dm-1\n"
"/dev/disk/by-id/wwn-0x600a098000aad73f00000a3f5a275dc8<co xml:id=\"mp-ref-wwn"
"\"/> -&gt; ../../dm-1\n"
"/dev/mapper/mpathb<co xml:id=\"mp-ref-mapper\"/> -&gt; ../dm-1"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2833
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t These two links use the map name for\t referring to the map. Thus the "
"links will change if the map name\t changes, for example if user friendly "
"names are disabled or enabled.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2840
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t This link uses the device mapper UUID, which is the WWID used by\t "
"<systemitem>multipath-tools</systemitem> prefixed by the string\t "
"<literal>dm-uuid-mpath-</literal> . It is independent\t of the map name.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2846
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The device mapper UUID is the preferred form to make sure\t "
"<emphasis>only multipath devices</emphasis> \t are referenced. For example, "
"the following line in\t <filename>/etc/lvm/lvm.conf</filename> \t rejects "
"all devices except multipath maps:\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2853
#, no-c-format
msgid "filter = [ \"a|/dev/disk/by-id/dm-uuid-mpath-.*|\", \"r|.*|\" ]"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2856
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t These are links that would normally point to path devices. The\t "
"multipath device took them over, because it has a higher udev\t link "
"priority (see <systemitem>udev(7)</systemitem> ).\t When the map is "
"destroyed or multipathing is turned off,\t they will still exist and point "
"to one of the path devices\t instead. This provides a means to reference a "
"device by\t its WWID, whether or not multipathing is active.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2868
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For <emphasis role=\"bold\">partitions</emphasis> on multipath maps created "
"by the <command>kpartx</command> tool, there are similar symbolic links, "
"derived from the parent device name or WWID and the partition number:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: informalexample
#: storage_multipath.xml:2874
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
" <screen>/dev/disk/by-id/dm-name-mpatha-part2 -&gt; ../../dm-5\n"
"/dev/disk/by-id/dm-uuid-part2-mpath-3600a098000aad1e300000b4b5a275d45 -"
"&gt; ../../dm-5\n"
"/dev/disk/by-id/scsi-3600a098000aad1e300000b4b5a275d45-part2 -&gt; ../../"
"dm-5\n"
"/dev/disk/by-id/wwn-0x600a098000aad1e300000b4b5a275d45-part2 -&gt; ../../"
"dm-5\n"
"/dev/disk/by-partuuid/1c2f70e0-fb91-49f5-8260-38eacaf7992b -&gt; ../../dm-5\n"
"/dev/disk/by-uuid/f67c49e9-3cf2-4bb7-8991-63568cb840a4 -&gt; ../../dm-5\n"
"/dev/mapper/mpatha-part2 -&gt; ../dm-5\n"
"</screen> "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2884
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Note that partitions often have <filename>by-uuid</filename> links, too, "
"referring not to the device itself but to the file system it contains. These "
"links are often preferrable. They are invariant even if the file system is "
"copied to a different device or partition."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2892
#, no-c-format
msgid "Map names in the initramfs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2893
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"When <command>dracut</command> builds an initramfs, it creates hard-coded "
"references to devices in the initramfs, using <filename>/dev/mapper/"
"$MAP_NAME</filename> references by default. These hard-coded references will "
"not be found during boot if the map names used in the initramfs do not match "
"the names used while the initramfs was built, causing boot failure. Normally "
"this will not happen, because <command>dracut</command> will add all "
"multipath configuration files to the initramfs. But problems can occur if "
"the initramfs is built from a different environment, for example in the "
"rescue system or during offline update. To protect against this, change "
"<command>dracut</command> 's <literal>persistent_policy</literal> setting, "
"as explained in <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-initrd-persistent\" xrefstyle="
"\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:2915
#, no-c-format
msgid "Miscellaneous options"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2917
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This section lists some useful <filename>multipath.conf</filename> options "
"that were not mentioned so far. See <systemitem>multipath.conf(5)</"
"systemitem> for a full list."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2924
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t verbosity"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2928
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Controls the log verbosity of both <command>multipath</command> and\t "
"<command>multipathd</command> . The command line option\t <option>-v</"
"option> overrides this setting for both commands. The value can be\t between "
"0 (only fatal errors) and 4 (verbose logging). The\t default is 2.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2938
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t uid_attrs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2942
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t This option enables an optimization for processing of udev events,\t so-"
"called &ldquo;uevent merging&rdquo;. It is useful in\t environments in which "
"hundreds of\t path devices my fail or reappear simultaneously.\t In order to "
"make sure that path WWIDs don't change\t (see <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-"
"conf-file-wwid\" xrefstyle=\"SecTitleOnPage\"/> ), the value should be set "
"exactly\t like this:\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:2952
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"defaults {\n"
"     uid_attrs \"sd:ID_SERIAL dasd:ID_UID nvme:ID_WWN\"\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2958
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t skip_kpartx"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2962
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If set to <literal>yes</literal> for a multipath device (default is\t "
"<literal>no</literal> ), don't create partition devices\t on top of the "
"given device (see <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-configuration-partitioning\" "
"xrefstyle=\"SecTitleOnPage\"/> ). Useful for multipath devices\t that are "
"provided to virtual machines. Previous &productname;\t releases achieved the "
"same effect with the parameter\t &ldquo; <literal>features 1 no_partitions</"
"literal> &rdquo;.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2975
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t max_sectors_kb"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2979
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Limit the maximum amount of data sent in a single I/O request for all\t "
"path devices of the multipath map.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:2986
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t ghost_delay"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:2990
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t On active/passive arrays, it can happen that passive paths (in\t &ldquo;"
"ghost&rdquo; state) are probed before active paths.\t If the map was "
"activated immediately and I/O was sent, this would\t cause a possibly costly "
"path activation. This\t parameter specificies a time (in seconds) to wait "
"for active paths\t of the map to appear before activating the map.\t The "
"default is <literal>no</literal> (no ghost delay).\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:3002
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t recheck_wwid"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3006
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If set to <literal>yes</literal> (default is <literal>no</literal> ),\t "
"double check the WWID of restored paths after failure, and remove\t them if "
"the WWID has changed. This is a safety measure against data\t corruption.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:3015
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t enable_foreign"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3019
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t <systemitem>multipath-tools</systemitem> provides an plugin API for\t "
"other multipathing backends than Device Mapper multipath.\t The API supports "
"monitoring and displaying information about\t the multipath topology using "
"standard commands like\t <command>multipath -ll</command> .\t Modifying the "
"topology is unsupported.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3027
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The value of <literal>enable_foreign</literal> is a regular\t expression "
"to match against foreign library names.\t The default value is &ldquo; "
"<literal>NONE</literal> &rdquo;.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3032
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t &productname; ships the <literal>nvme</literal> plugin, which\t adds "
"support for NVMe native multipathing\t (see <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-"
"hardware-implementations\" xrefstyle=\"SecTitleOnPage\"/> ). To enable the "
"nvme plugin, set\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:3038
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"defaults {\n"
"    enable_foreign nvme\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:3045
#, no-c-format
msgid "Handling unreliable (&ldquo;marginal&rdquo;) path devices"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3046
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Unstable conditions in the fabric can cause path devices to behave "
"erratically. They exhibit frequent I/O errors, recover, and fail again. Such "
"path devices are also denoted &ldquo;marginal&rdquo; or &ldquo;shaky&rdquo; "
"paths. This section summarizes the options that <systemitem>multipath-tools</"
"systemitem> provides to deal with this problem."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:3056
#, no-c-format
msgid "multipathd's marginal path checking algorithm"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3057
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t If a path device exhibits a second failure (good → bad transition)\t "
"before <literal>marginal_path_double_failed_time</literal> \t elapses after "
"a first failure, <command>multipathd</command> \t starts monitoring the path "
"at a rate of 10 requests per second,\t for a monitoring period of\t "
"<literal>marginal_path_err_sample_time</literal> . If the error rate\t "
"during the monitoring period exceeds\t "
"<literal>marginal_path_err_rate_threshold</literal> , the path\t is "
"classified as marginal. After\t <literal>marginal_path_err_recheck_gap_time</"
"literal> ,\t the path transitions to normal state again."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3070
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t This algorithm is used if all four numeric\t <literal>marginal_path_</"
"literal> parameters\t are set to a positive value,\t and "
"<literal>marginal_pathgroups</literal> is\t not set to <literal>fpin</"
"literal> .\t It is available since &sles;&nbsp;15&nbsp;SP1 and\t &sles;"
"&nbsp;12&nbsp;SP5."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:3083
#, no-c-format
msgid "marginal_path_double_failed_time"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3085
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Maximum time (in seconds)\t between two path failures that triggers\t "
"path monitoring.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:3093
#, no-c-format
msgid "marginal_path_err_sample_time"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3095
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t Length (in seconds) of the path monitoring interval.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:3101
#, no-c-format
msgid "marginal_path_err_rate_threshold"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3103
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t Minimum error rate (per thousand I/Os).\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:3109
#, no-c-format
msgid "marginal_path_err_recheck_gap_time"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3111
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t Time (in seconds) to keep the path in marginal state.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:3117
#, no-c-format
msgid "marginal_pathgroups"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3119
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t This option is available since\t &productnameshort;&nbsp;15SP3.\t "
"Possible values are:\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:3126
#, no-c-format
msgid "off"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3128
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\t Marginal state is determined by <command>multipathd</command> (see "
"above).\t\t Marginal paths are not reinstated\t\t as long as they remain in "
"marginal state. This is the\t\t default, and the behavior in &sles; releases "
"before SP3,\t\t where the <literal>marginal_pathgroups</literal> option was "
"unavailable.\t\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:3138
#, no-c-format
msgid "on"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3140
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\t Like <literal>off</literal> , but instead of keeping them in\t\t failed "
"state, marginal paths are moved to a\t\t separate path group, which will be "
"assigned lower priority than\t\t all other path groups (see <xref linkend="
"\"sec-multipath-grouping\" xrefstyle=\"SecTitleOnPage\"/> ). Paths in this "
"path group will only\t\t be used for I/O if all paths in other path groups "
"have failed.\t\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:3151
#, no-c-format
msgid "fpin"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3153
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\t This setting is available from &productnameshort;&nbsp;15SP4.\t\t "
"Marginal path state is derived from FPIN events (see\t\t below).\t\t "
"Marginal paths are moved into a separate path group, as described\t\t for "
"<literal>off</literal> .\t\t This setting\t\t requires no further host-side "
"configuration. It is the\t\t recommended way to handle marginal paths on "
"Fibre Channel\t\t fabrics that support FPIN.\t\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:3165
#, no-c-format
msgid "FPIN based marginal path detection"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3166
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t\t <command>multipathd</command> listens for Fibre\t\t Channel Performance "
"Impact Notifications (FPIN).\t\t If an FPIN-LI (Link Integrity) event is "
"received for a\t\t path device, the path will enter marginal state. This "
"state will\t\t last until a RSCN or Link up event is received on the Fibre\t"
"\t channel adapter the device is connected to.\t\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3181
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A simpler algorithm using the parameters <literal>san_path_err_threshold</"
"literal> , <literal>san_path_err_forget_rate</literal> , and "
"<literal>san_path_err_recovery time</literal> is also available and "
"recommended for &sles;&nbsp;15 (GA). See the &ldquo;Shaky paths "
"detection&rdquo; secion in <systemitem>multipath.conf(5)</systemitem> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:3192
#, no-c-format
msgid "Best practice"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:3195
#, no-c-format
msgid "Best practices for configuration"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3197
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The large number of configuration directives is daunting at first. More "
"often than not (unless you are in a clustering environment), you will get "
"good results with an empty configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3202
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Here are some general recommendations for stand-alone servers. They are "
"<emphasis>not mandatory</emphasis> . See the documentation of the respective "
"parameters in the previous sections for background information."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:3208
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"defaults {\n"
"    deferred_remove      yes\n"
"    find_multipaths      smart\n"
"    enable_foreign       nvme\n"
"    marginal_pathgroups  fpin    # 15.4 only, if supported by fabric\n"
"}\n"
"devices {\n"
"    # A catch-all device entry.\n"
"    device {\n"
"        vendor                .*\n"
"        product               .*\n"
"        dev_loss_tmo          infinity\n"
"        no_path_retry         60            # 5 minutes\n"
"        path_grouping_policy  group_by_prio\n"
"        path_selector         \"historical-service-time 0\"\n"
"        reservation_key       file          # if using SCSI persistent "
"reservations\n"
"    }\n"
"    # Follow up with specific device entries below, they will take "
"precedence.\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3228
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"After modifying the <filename>/etc/multipath.conf</filename> file, apply "
"your settings as described in <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-conf-file-apply"
"\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:3235
#, no-c-format
msgid "Interpreting multipath I/O status"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:3236
